data</fgdcGeoform></presForm></idCitation><idAbs>The Horizon table lists the horizon(s) and related data for the referenced map unit component. If the horizon thickness is greater than zero (low=5, RV=8, high=12), the horizon exists everywhere this component occurs. If the horizon thickness includes zero (low=0, RV=1, high=3), the horizon may exist in some places, but not in other places. Horizons that have two distinct parts, such as E/B or E&Bt horizons, are recorded twice. data</fgdcGeoform></presForm></idCitation><idAbs>The Horizon Texture Group table lists the range of textures for the referenced horizon as a concatenation of horizon texture and texture modifier(s). For example, a horizon that is gravelly loamy sand in some places and gravelly loamy coarse sand in other places is shown as GR-LS on one row and GR-LCOS on another row in this table. The row with the typically occurring texture is identified as the RV row. Stratified textures are shown in one row. For example, a horizon that is stratified gravelly loamy fine sand and cobbly coarse sand is shown as SR- GR-LFS CB-COS on one row and the Stratified? column for that row is marked "yes". data</fgdcGeoform></presForm></idCitation><idAbs>The Component Parent Material Group table lists the concatenated string of parent material(s) in which the referenced map unit component formed based on entries in the Component Parent Material table. For example, a component formed in one parent material, such as loess, or one vertical sequence of parent materials, such as loamy glacial drift over silty residuum weathered from shale, has one row in this table. A component formed in one parent material in some locations, but another parent material (or sequence of parent materials) in other locations has two rows in this table, one for each parent material (or sequence of parent materials). <metadata><idinfo><citation><citeinfo><title>FEATLINE - xxSTATExx</title><geoform>vector digital data</geoform></citeinfo></citation><descript><abstract>This feature class represents the special soil features that are delineated as one or more lines. It is generally the most detailed level of soil geographic data developed by the National Cooperative Soil Survey. The information was prepared by digitizing maps, by compiling information onto a planimetric correct base and digitizing, or by revising digitized maps using remotely sensed and other information. This layer displays the location of features too small to delineate at the mapping scale, but they are large enough and contrasting enough to significantly influence use and management. The features are linked to attributes in the featdesc attribute table. The map data are in a state-wide extent format. </abstract><purpose>The dataset was created for use in national, regional, and state-wide resource planning and analysis of soils data. The Soil Survey Geographic (SSURGO) Database depicts information about the kinds and distribution of soils on the landscape. The soil map and data used in the SSURGO product were prepared by soil scientists as part of the National Cooperative Soil Survey.</purpose></descript><spdom><bounding><westbc>-82.336208</westbc><eastbc>-78.190389</eastbc><northbc>40.758823</northbc><southbc>37.870658</southbc></bounding></spdom><keywords><place><placekt>None</placekt><placekey>United States of America</placekey><placekey>xxSURVEYSxx</placekey><placekey>xxSTATExx</placekey><placekey>USA</placekey></place></keywords><accconst>None</accconst><useconst>None</useconst><datacred>Soil Survey Staff. It is generally the most detailed level of soil geographic data developed by the National Cooperative Soil Survey. The information was prepared by digitizing maps, by compiling information onto a planimetric correct base and digitizing, or by revising digitized maps using remotely sensed and other information. This layer displays the location of features too small to delineate at the mapping scale, but they are large enough and contrasting enough to significantly influence use and management. The features are linked to attributes in the featdesc attribute table. The map data are in a state-wide extent format. </SPAN></P></DIV></DIV></DIV></idAbs><idPurp>The dataset was created for use in national, regional, and state-wide resource planning and analysis of soils data. The Soil Survey Geographic (SSURGO) Database depicts information about the kinds and distribution of soils on the landscape. The soil map and data used in the SSURGO product were prepared by soil scientists as part of the National Cooperative Soil Survey.</idPurp><idCredit>Soil Survey Staff. dimension=""><measDesc>Certain node/geometry and topology GT- polygon/chain relationships are collected or generated to satisfy topological requirements (the GT-polygon corresponds to the soil delineation). Some of these requirements include: chains must begin and end at nodes, chains must connect to each other at nodes, chains do not extend through nodes, left and right GT-polygons are defined for each chain element and are consistent throughout, and the chains representing the limits of the file are free of gaps. Edge locations generally do not deviate from centerline to centerline by more than 0.01 inch.</measDesc><evalMethDesc>The tests of logical consistency are performed using vendor software. All internal polygons are tested for closure with vendor software and are checked on hard copy plots. </evalMethDesc></report><dataLineage><prcStep><stepDesc>The SSURGO dataset is a digital soil survey and generally is the most detailed level of soil geographic data developed by the National Cooperative Soil Survey. The information was prepared by digitizing maps, by compiling information onto a planimetric correct base and digitizing, or by revising digitized maps using remotely sensed and other information. This dataset consists of georeferenced digital map data and computerized attribute data. The map data are in a soil survey area extent format and include a detailed, field verified inventory of soils and miscellaneous areas that normally occur in a repeatable pattern on the landscape and that can be cartographically shown at the scale mapped. The soil map units are linked to attributes in the National Soil Information System (NASIS) relational database, which gives the proportionate extent of the component soils and their properties.</stepDesc><stepProc><rpOrgName>U.S. Department of Agriculture, Natural Resources Conservation Service, National Soil Survey Center</rpOrgName><rpCntInfo><cntAddress addressType="postal"><delPoint>100 Centennial Mall North</delPoint><delPoint>Federal Building, Room 152</delPoint><city>Lincoln</city><adminArea>NE</adminArea><postCode>68508-3866</postCode><eMailAdd>SoilsHotline@usda.gov</eMailAdd><country>US</country></cntAddress></rpCntInfo><displayName>U.S. Department of Agriculture, Natural Resources Conservation Service, National Soil Survey Center</displayName><role><RoleCd value="007"/></role><displayName>U.S. Department of Agriculture, Natural Resources Conservation Service, National Soil Survey Center</displayName></stepProc><stepSrc type="produced"><srcDesc>Soil Survey Geographic (SSURGO) database vector data</srcDesc><srcMedName><MedNameCd value="015"/></srcMedName><srcScale><rfDenom>24000</rfDenom></srcScale><srcCitatn><resTitle>Soil Survey Geographic (SSURGO) Database for Soil Survey Areas</resTitle><citOnlineRes><linkage>http://websoilsurvey.nrcs.usda.gov</linkage><orFunct><OnFunctCd value="001"/></orFunct></citOnlineRes><presForm><fgdcGeoform>vector digital data</fgdcGeoform><PresFormCd value="005"/></presForm></srcCitatn></stepSrc></prcStep><prcStep><stepDesc>All available SSURGO data were downloaded from Web Soil Survey to a local cache. As part of the download process, the tabular data for each survey were imported into individual SSURGO template databases (MS Access format) using a custom set of ‘SSURGO Download Tools’ for ArcGIS 10.x. For each state or territory, intersecting SSURGO datasets were identified using the 'laoverlap' table (Legend Area Overlap). The selected datasets were merged and converted from shapefile and MS Access tables into a single ESRI file geodatabase for that state or territory. The data were not clipped to a state boundary, thus in some instances feature classes may extend beyond a state's boundary. All datasets were projected from the original Geographic WGS 1984 coordinate system to the appropriate Albers Equal Area Conic coordinate system. Relationship classes between tables and feature classes were created in the It is generally the most detailed level of soil geographic data developed by the National Cooperative Soil Survey. The information was prepared by digitizing maps, by compiling information onto a planimetric correct base and digitizing, or by revising digitized maps using remotely sensed and other information. This layer displays the location of features too small to delineate at the mapping scale, but they are large enough and contrasting enough to significantly influence use and management. The features are linked to attributes in the featdesc attribute table. The map data are in a state-wide extent format.</abstract><purpose>The dataset was created for use in national, regional, and state-wide resource planning and analysis of soils data. The Soil Survey Geographic (SSURGO) Database depicts information about the kinds and distribution of soils on the landscape. The soil map and data used in the SSURGO product were prepared by soil scientists as part of the National Cooperative Soil Survey.</purpose></descript><spdom><bounding><westbc>-82.771134</westbc><eastbc>-77.526833</eastbc><northbc>40.803304</northbc><southbc>36.855850</southbc></bounding></spdom><keywords><place><placekt>None</placekt><placekey>United States of America</placekey><placekey>xxSURVEYSxx</placekey><placekey>xxSTATExx</placekey><placekey>USA</placekey></place></keywords><accconst>None</accconst><useconst>None</useconst><datacred>Soil Survey Staff. It is generally the most detailed level of soil geographic data developed by the National Cooperative Soil Survey. The information was prepared by digitizing maps, by compiling information onto a planimetric correct base and digitizing, or by revising digitized maps using remotely sensed and other information. This layer displays the location of features too small to delineate at the mapping scale, but they are large enough and contrasting enough to significantly influence use and management. The features are linked to attributes in the featdesc attribute table. The map data are in a state-wide extent format.</SPAN></P><P><SPAN /></P></DIV></DIV></DIV></idAbs><idPurp>The dataset was created for use in national, regional, and state-wide resource planning and analysis of soils data. The Soil Survey Geographic (SSURGO) Database depicts information about the kinds and distribution of soils on the landscape. The soil map and data used in the SSURGO product were prepared by soil scientists as part of the National Cooperative Soil Survey.</idPurp><idCredit>Soil Survey Staff. SSURGO dataset is a digital soil survey and generally is the most detailed level of soil geographic data developed by the National Cooperative Soil Survey. The information was prepared by digitizing maps, by compiling information onto a planimetric correct base and digitizing, or by revising digitized maps using remotely sensed and other information. This dataset consists of georeferenced digital map data and computerized attribute data. The map data are in a soil survey area extent format and include a detailed, field verified inventory of soils and miscellaneous areas that normally occur in a repeatable pattern on the landscape and that can be cartographically shown at the scale mapped. The soil map units are linked to attributes in the National Soil Information System (NASIS) relational database, which gives the proportionate extent of the component soils and their properties.</stepDesc><stepProc><rpOrgName>U.S. Department of Agriculture, Natural Resources Conservation Service, National Soil Survey Center</rpOrgName><rpCntInfo><cntAddress addressType="postal"><delPoint>100 Centennial Mall North</delPoint><delPoint>Federal Building, Room 152</delPoint><city>Lincoln</city><adminArea>NE</adminArea><postCode>68508-3866</postCode><eMailAdd>SoilsHotline@usda.gov</eMailAdd><country>US</country></cntAddress></rpCntInfo><displayName>U.S. Department of Agriculture, Natural Resources Conservation Service, National Soil Survey Center</displayName><role><RoleCd value="007"/></role><displayName>U.S. Department of Agriculture, Natural Resources Conservation Service, National Soil Survey Center</displayName></stepProc><stepSrc type="produced"><srcDesc>Soil Survey Geographic (SSURGO) database vector data</srcDesc><srcMedName><MedNameCd value="015"/></srcMedName><srcScale><rfDenom>24000</rfDenom></srcScale><srcCitatn><resTitle>Soil Survey Geographic (SSURGO) Database for Soil Survey Areas</resTitle><citOnlineRes><linkage>http://websoilsurvey.nrcs.usda.gov</linkage><orFunct><OnFunctCd value="001"/></orFunct></citOnlineRes><presForm><fgdcGeoform>vector digital data</fgdcGeoform><PresFormCd value="005"/></presForm></srcCitatn></stepSrc></prcStep><prcStep><stepDesc>All available SSURGO data were downloaded from Web Soil Survey to a local cache. As part of the download process, the tabular data for each survey were imported into individual SSURGO template databases (MS Access format) using a custom set of ‘SSURGO Download Tools’ for ArcGIS 10.x. For each state or territory, intersecting SSURGO datasets were identified using the 'laoverlap' table (Legend Area Overlap). The selected datasets were merged and converted from shapefile and MS Access tables into a single ESRI file geodatabase for that state or territory. The data were not clipped to a state boundary, thus in some instances feature classes may extend beyond a state's boundary. All datasets were projected from the original Geographic WGS 1984 coordinate system to the appropriate Albers Equal Area Conic coordinate system. Relationship classes between tables and feature classes were created in the geodatabase.</stepDesc><stepProc><editorSource>external</editorSource><editorDigest>74669282e3bb2567255d1a5356fd4b9b</editorDigest><rpOrgName>U.S. Department of Agriculture, Natural Resources map unit symbol uniquely identifies each map unit delineation. Each symbol corresponds to a map unit name. The map unit key is used to link to information in the National Soil Information System tables.
Map Unit Delineations are described by the National Soil Information System database. This attribute database gives the proportionate extent of the component soils and the properties for each soil. The database contains both estimated and measured data on the physical and chemical soil properties and soil interpretations for engineering, water management, recreation, agronomic, woodland, range, and wildlife uses of the soil.</eaover><eadetcit>U.S. Department of Agriculture. 1999. The information was prepared by digitizing maps, by compiling information onto a planimetric correct base and digitizing, or by revising digitized maps using remotely sensed and other information.</SPAN></P><P><SPAN>This dataset consists of georeferenced digital map data and computerized attribute data. The map data are in a state-wide extent format and include a detailed, field verified inventory of soils and miscellaneous areas that normally occur in a repeatable pattern on the landscape and that can be cartographically shown at the scale mapped. The soil map units are linked to attributes in the National Soil Information System relational database, which gives the proportionate extent of the component soils and their properties.</SPAN></P></DIV></DIV></DIV></idAbs><idPurp>The dataset was created for use in national, regional, and state-wide resource planning and analysis of soils data. The Soil Survey Geographic (SSURGO) Database depicts information about the kinds and distribution of soils on the landscape. The soil map and data used in the SSURGO product were prepared by soil scientists as part of the National Cooperative Soil Survey.</idPurp><idCredit>Soil Survey Staff. SSURGO dataset is a digital soil survey and generally is the most detailed level of soil geographic data developed by the National Cooperative Soil Survey. The information was prepared by digitizing maps, by compiling information onto a planimetric correct base and digitizing, or by revising digitized maps using remotely sensed and other information. This dataset consists of georeferenced digital map data and computerized attribute data. The map data are in a soil survey area extent format and include a detailed, field verified inventory of soils and miscellaneous areas that normally occur in a repeatable pattern on the landscape and that can be cartographically shown at the scale mapped. The soil map units are linked to attributes in the National Soil Information System (NASIS) relational database, which gives the proportionate extent of the component soils and their properties.</stepDesc><stepProc><rpOrgName>U.S. Department of Agriculture, Natural Resources Conservation Service, National Soil Survey Center</rpOrgName><rpCntInfo><cntAddress addressType="postal"><delPoint>100 Centennial Mall North</delPoint><delPoint>Federal Building, Room 152</delPoint><city>Lincoln</city><adminArea>NE</adminArea><postCode>68508-3866</postCode><eMailAdd>SoilsHotline@usda.gov</eMailAdd><country>US</country></cntAddress></rpCntInfo><displayName>U.S. Department of Agriculture, Natural Resources Conservation Service, National Soil Survey Center</displayName><role><RoleCd value="010"/></role></stepProc><stepSrc type="produced"><srcDesc>Soil Survey Geographic (SSURGO) database vector data</srcDesc><srcMedName><MedNameCd value="015"/></srcMedName><srcScale><rfDenom>24000</rfDenom></srcScale><srcCitatn><resTitle>Soil Survey Geographic (SSURGO) Database for Soil Survey Areas</resTitle><citOnlineRes><linkage>http://websoilsurvey.nrcs.usda.gov</linkage><orFunct><OnFunctCd value="001"/></orFunct></citOnlineRes><presForm><fgdcGeoform>vector digital data</fgdcGeoform><PresFormCd value="005"/></presForm><citId><identCode>NRCS</identCode></citId></srcCitatn></stepSrc></prcStep><prcStep><stepDesc>All available SSURGO data were downloaded from Web Soil Survey to a local cache. As part of the download process, the tabular data for each survey were imported into individual SSURGO template databases (MS Access format) using a custom set of ‘SSURGO Download Tools’ for ArcGIS 10.x. For each state or territory, intersecting SSURGO datasets were identified using the 'laoverlap' table (Legend Area Overlap). The selected datasets were merged and converted from shapefile and MS Access tables into a single ESRI file geodatabase for that state or territory. The data were not clipped to a state boundary, thus in some instances feature classes may extend beyond a state's boundary. All datasets were projected from the original Geographic WGS 1984 coordinate system to the appropriate Albers Equal Area Conic coordinate system. Relationship classes between tables and feature classes were created in the geodatabase.</stepDesc><stepProc><editorSource>external</editorSource><editorDigest>74669282e3bb2567255d1a5356fd4b9b</editorDigest><rpOrgName>U.S. Department of Agriculture, Natural Resources The information was prepared by digitizing maps, by compiling information onto a planimetric correct base and digitizing, or by revising digitized maps using remotely sensed and other information.This dataset consists of georeferenced digital map data and computerized attribute data. The map data are in a state-wide extent format and include a detailed, field verified inventory of soils and miscellaneous areas that normally occur in a repeatable pattern on the landscape and that can be cartographically shown at the scale mapped. The soil map units are linked to attributes in the National Soil Information System relational database, which gives the proportionate extent of the component soils and their properties.</abstract><purpose>The dataset was created for use in national, regional, and state-wide resource planning and analysis of soils data. The Soil Survey Geographic (SSURGO) Database depicts information about the kinds and distribution of soils on the landscape. The soil map and data used in the SSURGO product were prepared by soil scientists as part of the National Cooperative Soil Survey.</purpose></descript><keywords><place><placekt>None</placekt><placekey>United States of America</placekey><placekey>xxSURVEYSxx)</placekey><placekey>xxSTATExx</placekey><placekey>USA</placekey></place></keywords><accconst>None</accconst><useconst>None</useconst><datacred>Soil Survey Staff. value="005"/></scpLvl></dqScope><dataLineage><prcStep><stepDesc>The SSURGO dataset is a digital soil survey and generally is the most detailed level of soil geographic data developed by the National Cooperative Soil Survey. The information was prepared by digitizing maps, by compiling information onto a planimetric correct base and digitizing, or by revising digitized maps using remotely sensed and other information. This dataset consists of georeferenced digital map data and computerized attribute data. The map data are in a soil survey area extent format and include a detailed, field verified inventory of soils and miscellaneous areas that normally occur in a repeatable pattern on the landscape and that can be cartographically shown at the scale mapped. The soil map units are linked to attributes in the National Soil Information System (NASIS) relational database, which gives the proportionate extent of the component soils and their properties.</stepDesc><stepProc><rpOrgName>U.S. Department of Agriculture, Natural Resources Conservation Service, National Soil Survey Center</rpOrgName><rpCntInfo><cntAddress addressType="postal"><delPoint>100 Centennial Mall North</delPoint><delPoint>Federal Building, Room 152</delPoint><city>Lincoln</city><adminArea>NE</adminArea><postCode>68508-3866</postCode><eMailAdd>SoilsHotline@usda.gov</eMailAdd><country>US</country></cntAddress></rpCntInfo><displayName>U.S. Department of Agriculture, Natural Resources Conservation Service, National Soil Survey Center</displayName><role><RoleCd value="007"/></role></stepProc><stepSrc type="produced"><srcDesc>Soil Survey Geographic (SSURGO) database vector data</srcDesc><srcMedName><MedNameCd value="015"/></srcMedName><srcScale><rfDenom>24000</rfDenom></srcScale><srcCitatn><resTitle>Soil Survey Geographic (SSURGO) Database for Soil Survey Areas</resTitle><citOnlineRes><linkage>http://websoilsurvey.nrcs.usda.gov</linkage><orFunct><OnFunctCd value="001"/></orFunct></citOnlineRes><presForm><fgdcGeoform>vector digital data</fgdcGeoform><PresFormCd value="005"/></presForm><citId><identCode>NRCS</identCode></citId></srcCitatn></stepSrc></prcStep><prcStep><stepDesc>All available SSURGO data were downloaded from Web Soil Survey to a local cache. As part of the download process, the tabular data for each survey were imported into individual SSURGO template databases (MS Access format) using a custom set of ‘SSURGO Download Tools’ for ArcGIS 10.x. For each state or territory, intersecting SSURGO datasets were identified using the 'laoverlap' table (Legend Area Overlap). The selected datasets were merged and converted from shapefile and MS Access tables into a single ESRI file geodatabase for that state or territory. The data were not clipped to a state boundary, thus in some instances feature classes may extend beyond a state's boundary. All datasets were projected from the original Geographic WGS 1984 coordinate system to the appropriate Albers Equal Area Conic coordinate system. Relationship classes between tables and feature classes were created in the geodatabase.</stepDesc><stepProc><editorSource>external</editorSource><editorDigest>74669282e3bb2567255d1a5356fd4b9b</editorDigest><rpOrgName>U.S. Department of Agriculture, Natural Resources The information was prepared by digitizing maps, by compiling information onto a planimetric correct base and digitizing, or by revising digitized maps using remotely sensed and other information.This dataset consists of georeferenced digital map data and computerized attribute data. The map data are in a state-wide extent format and include a detailed, field verified inventory of soils and miscellaneous areas that normally occur in a repeatable pattern on the landscape and that can be cartographically shown at the scale mapped. The soil map units are linked to attributes in the National Soil Information System relational database, which gives the proportionate extent of the component soils and their properties.</abstract><purpose>The dataset was created for use in national, regional, and state-wide resource planning and analysis of soils data. The Soil Survey Geographic (SSURGO) Database depicts information about the kinds and distribution of soils on the landscape. value="005"/></scpLvl></dqScope><dataLineage><prcStep><stepDesc>The SSURGO dataset is a digital soil survey and generally is the most detailed level of soil geographic data developed by the National Cooperative Soil Survey. The information was prepared by digitizing maps, by compiling information onto a planimetric correct base and digitizing, or by revising digitized maps using remotely sensed and other information. This dataset consists of georeferenced digital map data and computerized attribute data. The map data are in a soil survey area extent format and include a detailed, field verified inventory of soils and miscellaneous areas that normally occur in a repeatable pattern on the landscape and that can be cartographically shown at the scale mapped. The soil map units are linked to attributes in the National Soil Information System (NASIS) relational database, which gives the proportionate extent of the component soils and their properties.</stepDesc><stepProc><rpOrgName>U.S. Department of Agriculture, Natural Resources Conservation Service, National Soil Survey Center</rpOrgName><rpCntInfo><cntAddress addressType="postal"><delPoint>100 Centennial Mall North</delPoint><delPoint>Federal Building, Room 152</delPoint><city>Lincoln</city><adminArea>NE</adminArea><postCode>68508-3866</postCode><eMailAdd>SoilsHotline@usda.gov</eMailAdd><country>US</country></cntAddress></rpCntInfo><displayName>U.S. Department of Agriculture, Natural Resources Conservation Service, National Soil Survey Center</displayName><role><RoleCd value="007"/></role><displayName>U.S. Department of Agriculture, Natural Resources Conservation Service, National Soil Survey Center</displayName></stepProc><stepSrc type="produced"><srcDesc>Soil Survey Geographic (SSURGO) database vector data</srcDesc><srcMedName><MedNameCd value="015"/></srcMedName><srcScale><rfDenom>24000</rfDenom></srcScale><srcCitatn><resTitle>Soil Survey Geographic (SSURGO) Database for Soil Survey Areas</resTitle><citOnlineRes><linkage>http://websoilsurvey.nrcs.usda.gov</linkage><orFunct><OnFunctCd value="001"/></orFunct></citOnlineRes><presForm><fgdcGeoform>vector digital data</fgdcGeoform><PresFormCd value="005"/></presForm></srcCitatn></stepSrc></prcStep><prcStep><stepDesc>All available SSURGO data were downloaded from Web Soil Survey to a local cache. As part of the download process, the tabular data for each survey were imported into individual SSURGO template databases (MS Access format) using a custom set of ‘SSURGO Download Tools’ for ArcGIS 10.x. For each state or territory, intersecting SSURGO datasets were identified using the 'laoverlap' table (Legend Area Overlap). The selected datasets were merged and converted from shapefile and MS Access tables into a single ESRI file geodatabase for that state or territory. The data were not clipped to a state boundary, thus in some instances feature classes may extend beyond a state's boundary. All datasets were projected from the original Geographic WGS 1984 coordinate system to the appropriate Albers Equal Area Conic coordinate system. Relationship classes between tables and feature classes were created in the The information was prepared by digitizing maps, by compiling information onto a planimetric correct base and digitizing, or by revising digitized maps using remotely sensed and other information. This dataset consists of georeferenced digital map data and computerized attribute data. The map data are in a soil survey area extent format and include a detailed, field verified inventory of soils and miscellaneous areas that normally occur in a repeatable pattern on the landscape and that can be cartographically shown at the scale mapped. The soil map units are linked to attributes in the National Soil Information System (NASIS) relational database, which gives the proportionate extent of the component soils and their properties.</procdesc><srcused>NRCS</srcused></procstep><procstep><procdesc>State-wide file geodatabases (ESRI) were exported from the October 15, 2012 snapshot of the NRCS Soil Data Mart at the National Soil Survey Center in Lincoln, Nebraska. Software used for all processes was ArcGIS 10.1. All existing SSURGO features and attributes were selected using the NASIS 'Legend Area Overlap' table to identify non-MLRA (Major Land Resource Area) soil survey areas that intersect this particular 'State or Territory'. The data were not clipped to a state boundary, thus in some instances feature classes may extend beyond a state's boundary. All conterminous United States (CONUS) datasets were projected from the original Geographic NAD83 coordinate system to 'Albers_Conical_Equal_Area'. Relationship classes between tables and feature classes were created in the geodatabase.</procdesc><srcused>NRCS</srcused><procdate>20121120</procdate></procstep><procstep><procdesc>A new table 'Lookup_Mukey' was created in order to facilitate the conversion of the MUPOLYGON feature class from polygon to raster. This table was derived from the MAPUNIT table in the Soil Data Mart and contains 'MUKEY' values for all soil surveys in the October 2012 Soil Data Mart database, not just those present in this geodatabase feature class. The table also contains an integer value attribute named 'CellValue'. This is the value used to generate the raster layer. 'CellValue' corresponds directly to the MUKEY value of the MAPUNIT table.</procdesc><procdate>20121120</procdate></procstep><procstep><procdesc>On xxTODAYxx, a 10 meter file geodatabase raster layer was created by converting the 'MUPOLYGON' feature class from feature to raster using 'PolygonToRaster' with the 'MAXIMUM_COMBINED_AREA' option in ArcGIS 10.x. The raster layer was snapped to the 2006 NLCD raster for CONUS. Pyramids and a raster attribute table were created. Using the 'Lookup_Mukey' table, a single attribute 'MUKEY' was added to the raster attribute table to facilitate joins with the attribute data.</procdesc><srcused>NLCD</srcused><procdate>20121120</procdate></procstep></lineage></dataqual><spdoinfo><direct>Vector</direct><rastinfo><rasttype>Grid Sync="TRUE">0</attscale></attr></detailed><overview><eaover>Map Unit Delineations are closed polygons that may be dominated by a single soil or miscellaneous area component plus allowable similar or dissimilar soils, or they can be geographic mixtures of groups of soils or soils and miscellaneous areas.
The map unit symbol uniquely identifies each map unit delineation. Each symbol corresponds to a map unit name. The map unit key is used to link to information in the National Soil Information System tables.
Map Unit Delineations are described by the National Soil Information System database. This attribute database gives the proportionate extent of the component soils and the properties for each soil. The database contains both estimated and measured data on the physical and chemical soil properties and soil interpretations for engineering, water management, recreation, agronomic, woodland, range, and wildlife uses of the soil.</eaover><eadetcit>U.S. Department of Agriculture. 1999. The information was prepared by digitizing maps, by compiling information onto a planimetric correct base and digitizing, or by revising digitized maps using remotely sensed and other information.</SPAN></P><P><SPAN>This dataset consists of georeferenced digital map data and computerized attribute data. The map data are in a state-wide extent format and include a detailed, field verified inventory of soils and miscellaneous areas that normally occur in a repeatable pattern on the landscape and that can be cartographically shown at the scale mapped. The soil map units are linked to attributes in the National Soil Information System relational database, which gives the proportionate extent of the component soils and their properties.</SPAN></P></DIV></DIV></DIV></idAbs><idPurp>The dataset was created for use in national, regional, and state-wide resource planning and analysis of soils data. The Soil Survey Geographic (SSURGO) Database depicts information about the kinds and distribution of soils on the landscape. The soil map and data used in the SSURGO product were prepared by soil scientists as part of the National Cooperative Soil Survey.</idPurp><idCredit>Soil Survey Staff. The information was prepared by digitizing maps, by compiling information onto a planimetric correct base and digitizing, or by revising digitized maps using remotely sensed and other information. This dataset consists of georeferenced digital map data and computerized attribute data. The map data are in a soil survey area extent format and include a detailed, field verified inventory of soils and miscellaneous areas that normally occur in a repeatable pattern on the landscape and that can be cartographically shown at the scale mapped. As part of the download process, the tabular data for each survey were imported into individual SSURGO template databases (MS Access format) using a custom set of ‘SSURGO Download Tools’ for ArcGIS 10.x. For each state or territory, intersecting SSURGO datasets were identified using the 'laoverlap' table (Legend Area Overlap). The selected datasets were merged and converted from shapefile and MS Access tables into a single ESRI file geodatabase for that state or territory. The data were not clipped to a state boundary, thus in some instances feature classes may extend beyond a state's boundary. All datasets were projected from the original Geographic WGS 1984 coordinate system to the appropriate Albers Equal Area Conic coordinate system. Relationship classes between tables and feature classes were created in the geodatabase.</stepDesc><stepSrc type="used"><srcCitatn><resTitle>Soil Survey Geographic (SSURGO) database vector <metadata><idinfo><citation><citeinfo><origin>U.S. Department of Agriculture, Natural Resources Conservation Service</origin><pubdate>20140120</pubdate><title>Gridded Soil Survey Geographic (gSSURGO) Database for xxSTATExx</title><edition>FY2014</edition><geoform>vector and raster digital map data and tabular digital data</geoform><serinfo><sername>gSSURGO</sername><issue>FY2014</issue></serinfo><pubinfo><pubplace>Fort Worth, Texas</pubplace><publish>U.S. Department of Agriculture, Natural Resources Conservation Service</publish></pubinfo><onlink>URL:http://datagateway.nrcs.usda.gov</onlink></citeinfo></citation><descript><abstract>This dataset is called the Gridded SSURGO (gSSURGO) Database and is derived from the Soil Survey Geographic (SSURGO) Database. SSURGO is generally the most detailed level of soil geographic data developed by the National Cooperative Soil Survey (NCSS) in accordance with NCSS mapping standards. The tabular data represent the soil attributes, and are derived from properties and characteristics stored in the National Soil Information System (NASIS). The gSSURGO data were prepared by merging traditional SSURGO digital vector map and tabular data into State-wide extents, and adding a state-wide gridded map layer derived from the polygon layer. The gridded map layer is offered in an ArcGIS file geodatabase raster format. The raster map data have a 10 meter cell size that approximates the vector polygons in an Albers Equal Area projection. Each cell (and polygon) is linked to a map unit identifier called the map unit key. The unique map unit key is used to link to raster cells and polygons to mapunit and muaggatt attribute tables.</abstract><purpose>The Gridded SSURGO dataset was created for use in national, regional, and state-wide resource planning and analysis of soils data. The dataset consists of soils data in raster, vector and attribute tables. The raster map layer data can be readily combined with other national, regional, and local raster layers, e.g., National Land Cover Database (NLCD), the National Agricultural Statistics Service (NASS) Crop Data Layer, or the National Elevation Dataset (NED).</purpose></descript><timeperd><timeinfo><sngdate><caldate>20121015</caldate></sngdate></timeinfo><current>publication date</current></timeperd><status><progress>In work</progress><update>Annually</update></status><spdom><bounding><westbc>-174.837525</westbc><eastbc>-123.540711</eastbc><northbc>65.978601</northbc><southbc>54.199787</southbc></bounding></spdom><keywords><place><placekt>Counties and County Equivalents of the States of the United States and the District of Columbia (FIPS Pub 6-3)</placekt><placekey>United States of America</placekey><placekey>USA</placekey><placekey>xxSTATExx</placekey><placekey>xxSURVEYSxx</placekey></place><theme><themekey>soils, raster, Geospatial Data Gateway, gridded, Soil Survey, GDG, gSSURGO, SSURGO</themekey></theme></keywords><accconst>None</accconst><useconst>The U.S. Department of Agriculture, Natural Resources Conservation Service, should be acknowledged as the data source in products derived from these data. The information was prepared by digitizing maps, by compiling information onto a planimetric correct base and digitizing, or by revising digitized maps using remotely sensed and other information. This dataset consists of georeferenced digital map data and computerized attribute data. The map data are in a soil survey area extent format and include a detailed, field verified inventory of soils and miscellaneous areas that normally occur in a repeatable pattern on the landscape and that can be cartographically shown at the scale mapped. The soil map units are linked to data in the gSSURGO attribute tables, which gives the proportionate extent of the component soils and their properties.</procdesc><srcused>NRCS</srcused><procdate>20140120</procdate></procstep><procstep><procdesc>State-wide file geodatabases (ESRI) were exported from the January, 2014 SSURGO downloads from Web Soil Survey. Software used for all processes was ArcGIS 10.1. All existing SSURGO features and attributes were selected by querying the online Soil Data Access database to identify non-MLRA (Major Land Resource Area) soil survey areas that intersect this particular 'State or Territory'. The spatial data were projected from the original Geographic WGS 1984 coordinate system to Albers Equal Area Conic.</procdesc><srcused>NRCS</srcused><procdate>20140120</procdate></procstep><procstep><procdesc>Metadata was updated.</procdesc><srcused>NLCD</srcused><procdate>20140120</procdate></procstep><procstep><procdesc>An integer version of the mapunit key was created and used to generate the raster layer. After the raster attribute table was created, the character mapunit key was regenerated from those integer values.</procdesc><procdate>20140120</procdate></procstep><procstep><procdesc>A 10 meter file geodatabase raster layer was created by converting the 'MUPOLYGON' feature class from feature to raster using 'PolygonToRaster' with the 'MAXIMUM_COMBINED_AREA' option in ArcGIS 10.x. The raster layer was aligned to the NLCD raster. Raster statistics, pyramids and an attribute table containing mapunit key were created.</procdesc><srcused>NLCD</srcused><procdate>20140120</procdate></procstep></lineage></dataqual><spdoinfo><direct>Vector</direct><ptvctinf><sdtsterm><sdtstype>GT-polygon composed of chains</sdtstype><ptvctcnt>0</ptvctcnt></sdtsterm></ptvctinf><rastinfo><rasttype>Grid Cell</rasttype></rastinfo></spdoinfo><eainfo><overview xmlns=""><eaover>Map Unit Delineations are closed polygons that may be dominated by a single soil or miscellaneous area component plus allowable similar or dissimilar soils, or they can be geographic mixtures of groups of soils or soils and miscellaneous areas.
The map unit symbol uniquely identifies each map unit delineation. Each symbol corresponds to a map unit name. The map unit key is used to link to information in the National Soil Information System tables.
Map Unit Delineations are described by the National Soil Information System database. This attribute database gives the proportionate extent of the component soils and the properties for each soil. The database contains both estimated and measured data on the physical and chemical soil properties and soil interpretations for engineering, water management, recreation, agronomic, woodland, range, and wildlife uses of the soil.
Raster cell locations are based on map unit delineations which are closed polygons that may be dominated by a single soil or nonsoil component plus allowable similar or dissimilar soils, or they can be geographic mixtures of groups of soils or soils and nonsoil areas. The map unit key is used to link to information in the National Soil Information System (NASIS) tables. The mukey column and value was added to the raster attribute table to facilitate joins with the attribute data.</eaover><eadetcit>U.S. Department of Agriculture. 1999. xmlns=""><dqScope><scpLvl><ScopeCd value="005"/></scpLvl></dqScope><dataLineage><prcStep xmlns=""><stepDesc>The SSURGO dataset is a digital soil survey and generally is the most detailed level of soil geographic data developed by the National Cooperative Soil Survey. The information was prepared by digitizing maps, by compiling information onto a planimetric correct base and digitizing, or by revising digitized maps using remotely sensed and other information. This dataset consists of georeferenced digital map data and computerized attribute data. The map data are in a soil survey area extent format and include a detailed, field verified inventory of soils and miscellaneous areas that normally occur in a repeatable pattern on the landscape and that can be cartographically shown at the scale mapped. The soil map units are linked to attributes in the National Soil Information System (NASIS) relational database, which gives the proportionate extent of the component soils and their properties.</stepDesc><stepProc xmlns=""><rpOrgName>U.S. Department of Agriculture, Natural Resources Conservation Service, National Soil Survey Center</rpOrgName><rpCntInfo xmlns=""><cntAddress addressType="postal"><delPoint>100 Centennial Mall North</delPoint><delPoint>Federal Building, Room 152</delPoint><city>Lincoln</city><adminArea>NE</adminArea><postCode>68508-3866</postCode><eMailAdd>SoilsHotline@usda.gov</eMailAdd><country>US</country></cntAddress></rpCntInfo><displayName>U.S. Department of Agriculture, Natural Resources Conservation Service, National Soil Survey Center</displayName><role><RoleCd value="007"/></role><displayName>U.S. Department of Agriculture, Natural Resources Conservation Service, National Soil Survey Center</displayName></stepProc><stepSrc type="produced" xmlns=""><srcDesc>Soil Survey Geographic (SSURGO) database vector data</srcDesc><srcMedName><MedNameCd value="015"/></srcMedName><srcCitatn xmlns=""><resTitle>Soil Survey Geographic (SSURGO) Database for Soil Survey Areas</resTitle><citOnlineRes xmlns=""><linkage>http://websoilsurvey.nrcs.usda.gov</linkage><orFunct><OnFunctCd value="001"/></orFunct></citOnlineRes><presForm xmlns=""><fgdcGeoform>vector digital data</fgdcGeoform><PresFormCd value="005"/></presForm></srcCitatn></stepSrc></prcStep><prcStep xmlns=""><stepDesc>All available SSURGO data were downloaded from Web Soil Survey to a local cache. As part of the download process, the tabular data for each survey were imported into individual SSURGO template databases (MS Access format) using a custom set of ‘SSURGO Download Tools’ for ArcGIS 10.x. For each state or territory, intersecting SSURGO datasets were identified using the 'laoverlap' table (Legend Area Overlap). The selected datasets were merged and converted from shapefile and MS Access tables into a single ESRI file geodatabase for that state or territory. The data were not clipped to a state boundary, thus in some instances feature classes may extend beyond a state's boundary. All datasets were projected from the original Geographic WGS 1984 coordinate system to the appropriate Albers Equal Area Conic coordinate system. Relationship classes between tables and feature classes were created in the geodatabase.</stepDesc><stepProc xmlns=""><rpOrgName>U.S. Department of Agriculture, Natural Resources Conservation Service, National Geospatial Center of Excellence</rpOrgName><rpCntInfo xmlns=""><cntPhone><voiceNum tddtty="">800 672 5559</voiceNum><faxNum>817 509 3469</faxNum></cntPhone><cntAddress addressType="postal"><delPoint>501 West Felix Street</delPoint><city>Fort Worth</city><adminArea>TX</adminArea><postCode>76115</postCode><country>US</country></cntAddress></rpCntInfo><displayName>U.S. Department of Agriculture, Natural Resources Conservation Service, National Geospatial Center of Excellence</displayName><role><RoleCd value="005"/></role></stepProc><stepSrc type="used" xmlns=""><srcDesc>Soil Survey Geographic (SSURGO) database vector data</srcDesc><srcMedName><MedNameCd value="015"/></srcMedName><srcCitatn xmlns=""><resTitle>Soil Survey Geographic (SSURGO) database vector data</resTitle><citOnlineRes xmlns=""><linkage>http://websoilsurvey.nrcs.usda.gov</linkage><orFunct><OnFunctCd value="001"/></orFunct></citOnlineRes><presForm xmlns=""><fgdcGeoform>vector digital data</fgdcGeoform><PresFormCd value="005"/></presForm></srcCitatn></stepSrc></prcStep><prcStep xmlns=""><stepDesc>A 10 meter file geodatabase raster layer was created by converting the 'MUPOLYGON' feature class from feature to raster using 'PolygonToRaster' with the 'MAXIMUM_COMBINED_AREA' option in ArcGIS 10.x. Where available, the raster layer was aligned to the USGS NLCD raster. Pyramids and a raster attribute table were created. A single attribute 'MUKEY' was added to the raster attribute table to facilitate joins with the attribute data.</stepDesc><stepProc xmlns=""><rpOrgName>U.S. Department of Agriculture, Natural
